    <item>
      <title>Research Month: Addressing Diet-Related Implicit Bias and Strengthening Voices in Nutrition and Healthcare Collaboration at Interdisciplinary Research Building</title>
      <description><![CDATA[<div>  <img src="https://localist-images.azureedge.net/photos/52436109549825/huge/5f39d765a2c418ab47487b509a3a09c08c3d3009.jpg" style="width: 100%;" />  <div style="font-size: 0.9em; color: #555;"><strong>Tue, 07 Apr 2026</strong></div>  <div><p>The  Symposium will be hosted as part of Howard University Research Month to showcase research and educational outcomes from the Nourishing Futures project—an initiative that examines dietary behaviors, nutrition knowledge, health risks, and academic outcomes of Howard University students pursuing a healthcare-related discipline. As part of this project, we plan to develop and implement targeted nutrition-based interventions and strategies that empower students to make healthier choices and address barriers to meeting the Dietary Guidelines for Americans, including serving sizes for core elements like dairy that make up a healthy dietary pattern.</p>

<p> </p>

<p> </p>

<p>Guest Speakers: </p>

<p>Priscilla Michelle Mpasi, M.D., FAAP, Pediatrician, Christiana Care Health System. Keynote Speaker</p>

<p>Ashley Carter, MS, RD, LDN, Founding Member &amp; Co-Director, Eat Well Exchange, Inc. </p>

<p> </p>

<p>Host/Moderators: </p>

<p>Oluwakemi Adeola, Ph.D., RD, LDN, IFMCP, Clinical Assistant Professor, Nutritional Sciences, College of Nursing &amp; Allied Health Sciences  </p>

<p>Katherine M. Manuel, Ph.D., RD, LDN, FAND, Assistant Professor, Nutritional Sciences, College of Nursing &amp; Allied Health Sciences </p>

<p> </p>

<p>Student Presenters: </p>

<p>Grayce Amos, Research Assistant Nourishing Futures Research Project Nutritional Sciences, College of Nursing &amp; Allied Health Sciences  </p>

<p>Leah Biniam, Research Assistant Nourishing Futures Research Project, Nutritional Sciences, College of Nursing &amp; Allied Health Sciences  </p>

<p>Zaryah Stroman, Research Assistant Nourishing Futures Research Project, Nutritional Sciences, College of Nursing &amp; Allied Health Sciences  </p>

<p>Symposium Outcomes: </p>

<p>Increase awareness of implicit bias in dietary guidance.Strengthen collaboration and research in culturally responsive nutrition.Deepen understanding of evidence-based, dairy-inclusive healthy eating patterns.Promote culturally informed collaboration across healthcare disciplines.Expand professional development for students and early-career professionals of color.Strengthen Howard University’s leadership in nutrition and translational health research.</p>

<p><a href="https://events.howard.edu/event/research-month-addressing-diet-related-implicit-bias-and-strengthening-voices-in-nutrition-and-healthcare-collaboration">View on site</a> | <a href="mailto:?subject=I found an interesting event%3A Research Month%3A Addressing Diet-Related Implicit Bias and Strengthening Voices in Nutrition and Healthcare Collaboration&amp;body=I found an interesting event you may like%3A%0A%0A%0ADate%3A Apr 7%2C 2026%0A%0ADescription%3A%0AThe  Symposium will be hosted as part of Howard University Research Month to showcase research and educational outcomes from the Nourishing Futures project%E2%80%94an initiative that examines dietary behaviors%2C nutrition knowledge%2C health risks%2C and academic outcomes of Howard University students pursuing a healthcare-related discipline. As part of this project%2C we plan to develop and implement targeted nutrition-based interventions and strategies that empower students to make healthier choices and address barriers to meeting the Dietary Guidelines for Americans%2C including serving sizes for core elements like dairy that make up a healthy dietary pattern.%0A%0A %0A%0A %0A%0AGuest Speakers%3A %0A%0APriscilla Michelle Mpasi%2C M.D.%2C FAAP%2C Pediatrician%2C Christiana Care Health System. Keynote Speaker%0A%0AAshley Carter%2C MS%2C RD%2C LDN%2C Founding Member %26 Co-Director%2C Eat Well Exchange%2C Inc. %0A%0A %0A%0AHost%2FModerators%3A %0A%0AOluwakemi Adeola%2C Ph.D.%2C RD%2C LDN%2C IFMCP%2C Clinical Assistant Professor%2C Nutritional Sciences%2C College of Nursing %26 Allied Health Sciences  %0A%0AKatherine M. Manuel%2C Ph.D.%2C RD%2C LDN%2C FAND%2C Assistant Professor%2C Nutritional Sciences%2C College of Nursing %26 Allied Health Sciences %0A%0A %0A%0AStudent Presenters%3A %0A%0AGrayce Amos%2C Research Assistant Nourishing Futures Research Project Nutritional Sciences%2C College of Nursing %26 Allied Health Sciences  %0A%0ALeah Biniam%2C Research Assistant Nourishing Futures Research Project%2C Nutritional Sciences%2C College of Nursing %26 Allied Health Sciences  %0A%0AZaryah Stroman%2C Research Assistant Nourishing Futures Research Project%2C Nutritional Sciences%2C College of Nursing %26 Allied Health Sciences  %0A%0ASymposium Outcomes%3A %0A%0AIncrease awareness of implicit bias in dietary guidance.Strengthen collaboration and research in culturally responsive nutrition.Deepen understanding of evidence-based%2C dairy-inclusive healthy eating patterns.Promote culturally informed collaboration across healthcare disciplines.Expand professional development for students and early-career professionals of color.Strengthen Howard University%E2%80%99s leadership in nutrition and translational health research.%0A%0Ahttps%3A%2F%2Fevents.howard.edu%2Fevent%2Fresearch-month-addressing-diet-related-implicit-bias-and-strengthening-voices-in-nutrition-and-healthcare-collaboration%0A">Email this event</a></p></div></div>]]></description>
